Basically there are three types of scopes in custom directive, i.e. Shared, inherited, isolated. 
If you don&#39;t use `scope:{ reportsObj:&quot;=&quot; }` means it&#39;s a shared scope directive, it&#39;ll share scope of controller in which it&#39;s used. And that&#39;s why it&#39;ll work what you&#39;re expecting.

With another approach,
Using isolated scope just like what you&#39;ve used, update directive code as follows:

    angular.module(&#39;App&#39;).directive(&#39;reportsDirective&#39;,function(){
    return {
      scope:{
        reportsObj:&quot;=&quot;
      },
      templateUrl:&quot;./reports-analytics.html&quot;,
      link: function(scope,element,attrs){
        // directive logic
      }
     }
    })

 And update the use of directive in reportsController view as :

    &lt;reports-directive reports-obj=&quot;reportsObj &quot;&gt;&lt;/reports-directive&gt;
    
 Don&#39;t change code of `reportsController`  &amp; `reports-analytics.html`. This should also work as expected. But because of the use of &#39;=&#39; if you change reportsObj inside directive its value will change in outside controller also.

 Plunker **[Example][1]**.


  [1]: https://plnkr.co/edit/U05fnr4gGf9UV8IRYz9r?p=preview

